<bill id="DLM2999100" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" xml:lang="en-NZ" year.imprint="2010" bill.no="163" bill.type="government" stage="1" year="2010">
  <billdetail>
    <title>Governor-General Bill</title>
    <billtype>Government Bill</billtype>
    <explnote id="DLM2999101" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" rule-after="yes" rule-before="yes" bill.no="163" bill.type="government" stage="1" year="2010">
      <heading>Explanatory note</heading>
      <explnote.group>
        <heading>General policy statement</heading>
        <para>
          <text>This Bill implements the Law Commission's recommendations in Report 112, <emphasis style="italic">Review of the Civil List Act 1979 — the Governor-General</emphasis>. The Bill will repeal and replace Part 1 of the Civil List Act 1979 with updated and simpler financial arrangements for the support of the Governor-General and his or her programme.</text>
        </para>
      </explnote.group>
      <explnote.group>
        <heading>Clause by clause analysis</heading>
        <clause.desc>
          <para>
            <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 1</emphasis> is the title clause.</text>
          </para>
        </clause.desc>
        <clause.desc>
          <para>
            <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 2</emphasis> states that the Bill comes into effect on the day after the date on which it receives the Royal assent.</text>
          </para>
        </clause.desc>
        <explnote.part id="DLM2999102">
          <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes">1  </label>
          <heading>Provisions relating to remuneration, programme funding, and other payments concerning office of Governor-General</heading>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 3</emphasis> states that the Bill binds the Crown.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 4</emphasis> sets out a number of defined terms.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 5</emphasis> provides for payment to the Governor-General of a salary at a rate determined by the Remuneration Authority.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 6</emphasis> provides for payment to the Governor-General of an allowance for official expenses at a rate fixed by Order in Council.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 7</emphasis> provides for payment of a gross lump sum to a person who ceases to hold office as Governor-General, equivalent to the gross salary payable for the last 6 months that the person held office. Currently, section 3(4) of the Civil List Act 1979 provides for a lump sum equivalent to 3 months' salary. The change is to reflect the fact that currently the Governor-General's salary is tax exempt, but under this Bill this does not continue to be tax exempt. </text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 8</emphasis> provides for the payment of an annuity to a person who has held office as Governor-General at a yearly rate determined by the Remuneration Authority. The annuity is payable from the date that is 6 months after the person ceased to hold office.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 9</emphasis> provides for payment of an annuity to the spouse or partner of a former Governor-General from the date of the former Governor-General's death until the spouse or partner dies. If the former Governor-General dies after he or she leaves office, the spouse or partner must be paid the annuity at half the yearly rate at which an annuity would have been payable to the former Governor-General under <emphasis style="italic">clause 8</emphasis> had he or she not died (<emphasis style="italic">subclause (1)</emphasis>). The effect of <emphasis style="italic">subclause (2)</emphasis> is that if the Governor-General dies while in office, the spouse or partner must be paid the annuity at half the rate at which the annuity would have been payable to the former Governor-General based on the length of time that person served in office. </text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 10</emphasis> provides for compensation to be paid where the superannuation rights of a person appointed to the office of Governor-General, or the superannuation rights of the spouse or partner of that person, are adversely affected because of the appointment and the appointee has entered into a written agreement with the Minister of Finance, before taking up the office of Governor-General, for such compensation to be paid.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 11</emphasis> provides for the conditions of appointment of a Governor-General to include an agreement for that person and his or her spouse or partner to be provided with specified benefits and privileges when the person no longer holds office as Governor-General. These may be payments in relation to domestic travel and the use of chauffeur-driven cars. <emphasis style="italic">Subclause (2)</emphasis> requires a statement showing all the expenses incurred to provide any benefits and privileges under such an agreement, or under any agreement entered into with a former Governor-General before the commencement of the Bill, to be included in the audited financial statements of the Department of Internal Affairs in addition to the requirements in section 45B(2) of the Public Finance Act 1989. The effect of this requirement is that the statement will be included in the annual report of the Department of Internal Affairs presented to the House of Representatives under section 44 of the Public Finance Act 1989.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 12</emphasis> is a permanent legislative authority providing funding for the payments, benefits, and privileges referred to in <emphasis style="italic">clauses 5 to 11</emphasis> and <emphasis style="italic">clause 27(1)(d)</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 13</emphasis> is a permanent legislative authority providing funding to meet the costs of the Governor-General carrying out his or her duties of office in New Zealand.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 14</emphasis> is a permanent legislative authority providing funding to meet the costs of the Governor-General carrying out any duties of office outside New Zealand and the costs of travel by the Governor-General designate and his or her family members and staff for the purpose of the Governor-General designate's audience with the Sovereign.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 15</emphasis> provides that the Administrator of the Government continues to receive his or her judicial salary when that person acts as the Administrator of the Government. Currently, section 8 of the Civil List Act 1979 provides for the Administrator of the Government to be paid a salary in substitution for the person's judicial salary during any such period. This is calculated as a salary at half the rate of the Governor-General's salary and a salary at half the rate of the salary of the person's judicial office, or a salary at the rate of salary of the person's judicial office, whichever is greater. </text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
        </explnote.part>
        <explnote.part id="DLM2999103">
          <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes">2  </label>
          <heading>Miscellaneous provisions</heading>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clauses 16 and 17</emphasis> deal with how conflicting claims to the payment of an annuity under <emphasis style="italic">clause 9</emphasis> must be resolved. <emphasis style="italic">Clause 16(1)</emphasis> requires a person authorised by the Minister responsible for Ministerial Services to decide whether more than 1 person is entitled to the annuity and, if so, in what proportion the annuity is payable to each of them. However, the amount of the payment must not exceed the amount that would have been paid if only 1 person were entitled to it (<emphasis style="italic">subclause (2)</emphasis>). <emphasis style="italic">Clause 17</emphasis> gives a claimant who is dissatisfied with the authorised person's decision under <emphasis style="italic">clause 16</emphasis> the right to appeal to the High Court and the Court of Appeal. </text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clauses 18 to 20</emphasis> repeal the provisions of the Civil List Act 1979 relating to the office of Governor-General (Part 1 and section 25(1)(a)).</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clauses 21 to 24</emphasis> amend the Income Tax Act 2007 to make the Governor-General's salary taxable and subject to PAYE. The Governor-General's allowance continues to be tax exempt.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clauses 25 to 27</emphasis> deal with the consequences of the repeal of the Civil List Act 1979 provisions relating to the office of Governor-General. <emphasis style="italic">Clause 25 </emphasis> preserves the incumbent Governor-General's entitlements and position in respect of salary, allowance, lump sum on leaving office, compensation for lost or adversely affected superannuation rights, and travelling expenses as if the Bill had not been passed.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 26 </emphasis>confirms that the annuities payable in respect of the incumbent Governor-General and his or her spouse or partner are payable in accordance with <emphasis style="italic">clauses 8 and 9 </emphasis>of the Bill. </text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic"> Clause 27</emphasis> relates to the validity of certain Orders in Council, determinations of the Remuneration Authority, and agreements under the Civil List Act 1979 made before the commencement of the Bill. <emphasis style="italic">Subclauses (2) and (3)</emphasis> require certain annuities to be paid at the rate applicable at the commencement of the Bill until superseded by a determination of the Remuneration Authority under the Bill.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
        </explnote.part>
      </explnote.group>
    </explnote>
  </billdetail>
